					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12166886#post-4300669</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12166886/scp-4733#post-4300669</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sun, 07 Jul 2019 23:08:47 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Lt Flops</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1735419</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>No comments? Well, I'll be the first.</p> <p>I've noticed a few minor spelling and grammar errors in some of the latter logs, such as:</p> <blockquote> <p>&quot;A message not learned is a <strong>messagd</strong> not heard&quot;</p> </blockquote> <blockquote> <p>a slight ah, overreaction. <strong>he</strong> needed to remember her himself</p> </blockquote> <p>Which I think can be cleaned up without breaking any contest rules.</p> <p>Otherwise, I love this! This is a great companion piece to your tale and continues (and ends) Professor A.W.'s story adequately without simply expositing what happened. The people interviewed sound real and each one has a vibrant and memorable character. Your interpretation of dado is honestly refreshing, and his placement in the early 1900s feels natural. There's a lot of personality here, and even the more mundane sections (the descriptions of the anomalous machines) piqued my interest because their effects are unique. +1, and I'll say that this SCP is probably one of my favourite entries in the contest.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
